Lieutenant General '''Ian Rimbault Gleeson''' {{Post-nominals|country=ZAR|SSAG|SD|SM}} (born 1934)<ref name=Scientaria>{{cite journal|first1=C.J.|last1=Nöthling|first2=E.M.|last2=Meyers|title=Leaders through the years (1912-1982)|journal=Scientaria Militaria|year=1982|volume=12|issue=2|page=93|url=http://scientiamilitaria.journals.ac.za/pub/article/view/631}}</ref> is a retired South African Army officer who served as Chief of the Defence Staff.

He graduated from the Military Academy after attending Christian Brothers College in Pretoria and joined the Army in 1954.<ref name="ScIMil">{{cite journal | title=CIVILIAN-MILITARY INTERACTION ON THE MATIE CAMPUS: THE ‘BATTLE OF WILGENHOF’, 1957 | last1=Visser|first1=Deon | journal=Scientia Militaria, South African Journal of Military Studies | year=2009 | volume=37 | issue=2 | page=82}}</ref><ref name="FMail">{{cite journal | url=http://www.historicalpapers.wits.ac.za/inventories/inv_pdfo/AG1977/AG1977-A5-63-16-001-jpeg.pdf | title=The SADF: Supplement to the Financial Mail | journal=Financial Mail |date=July 1987  | page=14}}</ref> He became Officer Commanding [[2 South African Infantry Battalion]] in 1971 and in 1972 OC [[Walvis Bay military base]],<ref name=Scientaria /> and in July 1976 became [[General officer commanding|GOC]] [[101 Task Force]]. He then became ''Chief of Army Staff Operations'' on 15 January 1978<ref name=Scientaria /> before taking on the recreated post of ''Chief of Defence Force Staff''.<ref name="FMail" />

He retired in February 1990.<ref name="Burger">{{cite news| url=http://152.111.1.87/argief/berigte/dieburger/1990/03/01/2/12.html | title=Meiring kry bevel van leër | newspaper=[[Die Burger]] | date=1 March 1990 | accessdate=24 October 2014|language=Afrikaans|trans_title=Meiring gets command of Army}}</ref>

